{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628748","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628748"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:01:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:01:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17238"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17238"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9928"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77607"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9928"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17238"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63120"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"7614"},{"type":"tags","id":"10698"},{"type":"tags","id":"10709"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23278"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23283"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77607"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring DNA replication, a single nucleotide deletion occurs in the following coding sequence:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOriginal sequence: ATG CCG TAC GGA CTT\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMutated sequence: ATG CCG TAC GAC TT\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the effect of this single nucleotide deletion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Creates a new start codon","Deletes a single amino acid","Changes only the adjacent amino acid","Alters all subsequent amino acids","Maintains the original protein sequence"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe deletion of a single nucleotide disrupts the triplet reading frame of the genetic code. \u003Cstrong\u003EAlters all subsequent amino acids\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer because every codon after the deletion point will contain a different combination of nucleotides, resulting in a completely new amino acid sequence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConsider why the other options are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECreates a new start codon\u003C/strong\u003E - The deletion simply shifts existing nucleotides and does not generate the ATG sequence needed for a start codon\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeletes a single amino acid\u003C/strong\u003E - Rather than removing just one amino acid, the frameshift fundamentally changes the entire downstream sequence\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChanges only the adjacent amino acid\u003C/strong\u003E - The impact extends beyond just the next amino acid, affecting the entire remaining protein sequence\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaintains the original protein sequence\u003C/strong\u003E - The shifted reading frame makes this impossible as each codon now contains a different nucleotide combination\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFrameshift mutations frequently introduce premature stop codons (UAA, UAG, or UGA) in the new reading frame. This usually results in a shortened, non-functional protein product that may be targeted for degradation by cellular quality control mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Frameshift mutations occur when nucleotide insertions or deletions alter the reading frame of codons, resulting in a completely different amino acid sequence downstream.","Most frameshift mutations lead to premature stop codons and truncated proteins.","The genetic code is read in triplets (codons), so any shift in the reading frame affects all subsequent amino acids."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63120"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17238"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63120","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63120"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T20:31:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T20:33:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9928"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77607"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4940"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude